  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are some tips for socializing in grad student parties?",
  "response": "Socializing at grad student parties can be a great way to build connections, unwind, and network with peers. Here are some tips to make the most of these events:\n\n### 1. **Be Approachable**\n   - Smile, maintain open body language, and make eye contact when engaging with others.\n   - Avoid being glued to your phone; it can signal disinterest.\n\n### 2. **Start with Common Ground**\n   - Ask about their program, research, or field of study\u2014it\u2019s an easy conversation starter.\n   - Share something about your own work or interests to find commonalities.\n\n### 3. **Listen Actively**\n   - Show genuine interest in what others are saying by asking follow-up questions.\n   - Avoid dominating the conversation; let it flow naturally.\n\n### 4. **Keep It Casual**\n   - Grad student parties are often more relaxed than professional events, so don\u2019t feel pressured to discuss heavy academic topics.\n   - Share lighthearted topics like hobbies, favorite TV shows, or campus life.\n\n### 5. **Be Open to New Connections**\n   - Talk to people outside your department or program\u2014it\u2019s a great way to broaden your network.\n   - Introduce yourself confidently and remember names (it helps to repeat them when you hear them).\n\n### 6. **Balance Networking and Socializing**\n   - While networking is important, don\u2019t make every conversation about work or career goals.\n   - Focus on building genuine relationships rather than just professional connections.\n\n### 7. **Be Mindful of Your Etiquette**\n   - Watch your alcohol consumption; it\u2019s easy to overdo it at social events, but staying in control is key.\n   - Be respectful of others\u2019 boundaries and personal space.\n\n### 8. **Bring a Contribution**\n   - If it\u2019s a potluck or BYOB event, bring something to share\u2014it\u2019s a nice gesture and a good conversation starter.\n\n### 9. **Have an Exit Strategy**\n   - If you\u2019re feeling overwhelmed or the conversation has run its course, politely excuse yourself (e.g., \u201cI\u2019m going to grab another drink\u201d or \u201cIt was great talking with you!\u201d).\n\n### 10. **Follow Up**\n   - If you\u2019ve made a meaningful connection, consider exchanging contact info or connecting on LinkedIn to stay in touch.\n\nRemember, everyone is there to relax and connect, so don\u2019t stress too much. Just be yourself and enjoy the opportunity to meet new people!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
